<|repo_name|>yurikhanin/smart-home-system-project<|file_sep | # Smart Home System Project - Home Automation System using Raspberry Pi and Arduino 
 | 
 | This project is designed to automate home appliances using Raspberry Pi and Arduino.
 | The system uses a web interface for controlling devices and displays real-time sensor data.
 |
 | ## Features:
 | - Control lights and fans via web interface.
 | - Monitor temperature and humidity using DHT11 sensor.
 | - Display real-time sensor data on a web dashboard.
 | - Control devices remotely via MQTT protocol.
 |
 | ## Components:
 | - Raspberry Pi (Raspberry Pi Zero W recommended for low power consumption).
 | - Arduino Uno or similar microcontroller.
 | - DHT11 temperature and humidity sensor.
 | - Relay modules for controlling high-power devices like lights and fans.
 | - LEDs for status indication.
 |
 | ## Setup Instructions:
 |
 | ### Hardware Setup:
 | 1. Connect the DHT11 sensor to the Arduino's digital pin D7.
 | 2. Connect relay modules to Arduino's digital pins D8-D11 for controlling lights and fans.
 | 3. Connect LEDs to Arduino's digital pins D12-D13 for status indication.
 |
 | ### Software Setup:
 |
 | #### Raspberry Pi Setup:
 |
 ```bash 
 # Update package lists 
 sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade

 # Install required packages 
 sudo apt install python3-pip python3-flask python3-paho-mqtt

 # Clone repository 
 git clone https://github.com/yurikhanin/smart-home-system-project.git

 # Navigate to project directory 
 cd smart-home-system-project/raspberry_pi/
 ```
 |
 #### Arduino Setup:
 ```cpp 
 // Include necessary libraries 
 #include <DHT.h>
 #include <DHT_U.h>
 #include <MQTT.h>
 ```
 |
 #### MQTT Configuration:
 ```python 
 # Configure MQTT broker details in raspberry_pi/mqtt_config.py file

 BROKER_ADDRESS="your_mqtt_broker_address"
 BROKER_PORT="1883"
 CLIENT_ID="raspberry_pi_client"
 USERNAME="your_username" # Optional if authentication is required
 PASSWORD="your_password" # Optional if authentication is required

 TOPIC_LIGHTS="home/lights"
 TOPIC_FANS="home/fans"
 TOPIC_TEMPERATURE_HUMIDITY="home/sensors"
 ```
 |
 #### Web Interface Configuration:
 ```python 
 # Configure Flask application settings in raspberry_pi/app.py file

 DEBUG=True # Set to False in production environment

 PORT=5000 # Port number for Flask application

 MQTT_BROKER_ADDRESS="your_mqtt_broker_address"
 MQTT_BROKER_PORT="1883"
 MQTT_CLIENT_ID="raspberry_pi_client"
 MQTT_USERNAME="your_username" # Optional if authentication is required
 MQTT_PASSWORD="your_password" # Optional if authentication is required

 LIGHTS_TOPIC="home/lights"
 FANS_TOPIC="home/fans"
 TEMPERATURE_HUMIDITY_TOPIC="home/sensors"
 ```
 |
 ### Running the Application:
 ```bash 
 cd raspberry_pi/
 python app.py &
 ```
 ### Accessing Web Interface:
 Open a web browser and navigate to http://raspberry_pi_ip_address:<port_number>, where <port_number> is specified in app.py file.

### Controlling Devices via MQTT:

To control devices remotely via MQTT:

```bash  
# Publish messages to control lights or fans  
mosquitto_pub -h your_mqtt_broker_address -t home/lights -m "ON"  
mosquitto_pub -h your_mqtt_broker_address -t home/fans -m "ON"

# Subscribe to receive sensor data  
mosquitto_sub -h your_mqtt_broker_address -t home/sensors  
```
|
### Example Use Cases:

#### Turn On Lights:

Navigate to http://raspberry_pi_ip_address:<port_number>, click "Lights", then click "Turn On". Alternatively:

```bash  
mosquitto_pub -h your_mqtt_broker_address -t home/lights -m "ON"  
```

#### Turn Off Fans:

Navigate to http://raspberry_pi_ip_address:<port_number>, click "Fans", then click "Turn Off". Alternatively:

```bash  
mosquitto_pub -h your_mqtt_broker_address -t home/fans -m "OFF"  
```

#### View Sensor Data:

Navigate to http://raspberry_pi_ip_address:<port_number>. The dashboard will display real-time temperature and humidity readings.

|
### Notes:
- Ensure proper grounding when connecting high-power devices through relay modules.
- Adjust pin assignments in both Arduino sketch and Python code according to your hardware setup.
- Consider implementing security measures such as password protection or SSL encryption for production environments.

This project provides a foundation for building a comprehensive smart home system with additional features like scheduling automation rules or integrating other sensors/devices.



